# Project: GIX Course Petition Tracker
# Framework: Streamlit (Python)
# Python version: 3.11+

## Coding Standards
- Use Python 3.11+ features and syntax
- Use type hints for function parameters and return values
- Add docstrings to all functions (Google style)
- Use descriptive variable names (avoid single-letter names except for loop counters)
- Keep functions under 30 lines; extract helper functions when needed

## Streamlit Conventions
- Use st.set_page_config() at the top of the main app file
- Use st.tabs for navigation within a role, not st.sidebar
- Use st.cache_data for expensive computations
- Handle errors gracefully with try/except and display user-friendly messages with st.error() or st.warning()
- Use st.session_state for managing login state and form state

## Project Structure
- app.py: Main Streamlit application (login, student, advisor, instructor views)
- uploads/: Directory for uploaded PDF files (transcript, syllabus)
- petitions.json: Data storage for petition records
- .streamlit/config.toml: Streamlit theme configuration

## Visualization
- Prefer Plotly for interactive charts
- Use a consistent color palette: ["#1f77b4", "#ff7f0e", "#2ca02c", "#d62728", "#9467bd"]
- Always include chart titles, axis labels, and legends

## Business Logic
- Three roles: student, advisor, instructor
- Approval flow: Student submits → Advisor reviews → Instructor makes final decision
- Either advisor or instructor can reject; both must approve for final approval
- Student sees "Advisor Approved" as "Under Review" (hide internal flow)
- Status colors: gray (Submitted), blue (Advisor Approved), green (Approved), red (Rejected)
- Card background: white (unread), light yellow (viewed), light gray (decided)

## UI Conventions
- Bold all form field labels via CSS injection
- Rounded buttons (border-radius: 10px)
- Primary buttons use black background with white text
- Use st.divider() between sections for visual separation
